{"cursor":"4556","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Timocharis of Alexandria' (ca. 320 BC â 260 BC) was a Greek astronomer and\nphilosopher. Likely born in Alexandria, he was a contemporary of Euclid.\n\nWhat little is known about Timocharis comes from citations by Ptolemy in the\n[[Almagest]]. These indicate that Timocharis worked in Alexandria during the\n290s and 280s BCE. Ptolemy lists the declination of 18 stars as recorded by\nTimocharis or Aristillus in roughly the year 290 BCE. {{cite journal\n  | last=Newton | first=R. R. | year=1974 title=The obliquity of the ecliptic\n  | two millenia ago | journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society\n  | | volume=169 | pages=331â342 bibcode=1974MNRAS.169..331N }} Between\n  | 295 and 272 BCE, Timocharis recorded four lunar occultations and the passage\n  | of the planet Venus across a star. {{cite book first=Alexander |\n  | last=Jones | year=1999 title=Astronomical papyri from Oxyrhynchus volume=1â2\n  | | page=84 | isbn=0-87169-233-3 publisher=DIANE Publishing }} These\n  | were recorded using both the Egyptian and Athenian calendars. {{cite\n  | last=Jones | first=A. | year=1997 title=On the reconstructed Macedonian and\n  | Egyptian lunar calendars | volume=119 | pages=157â166 url=http://www.uni-koeln.de/phil-\n  | fak/ifa/zpe/downloads/1997/119pdf/119157.pdf accessdate=2009-09-10 }}\n  | The observed stellar passage by Venus may have occurred on October 12, 272\n  | BCE when the planet came within 15 arcminutes of the star η\n  | Virginis. {{cite book author=Fomenko, A. T.; Viï¸ aï¸¡cheslavovich, Vladimir\n  | Kalashnikov; NosovskiÄ­, Gleb Vladimirovich title=Geometrical and statistical\n  | methods of analysis of star configurations: dating Ptolemy's Almagest |\n  | page=215 | publisher=CRC Press | year=1993 isbn=0-8493-4483-2 }}\n\nThe observations by Timocharis are among the oldest Greek records that can\nbe assigned a specific date. They are only exceeded by records of the\nsummer solstice of 432 BCE, as noted by Euctemon and Meton. {{cite book\n  | first=James | last=Evans | year=1998 title=The History & Practice of Ancient\n  | Astronomy page=259 | publisher=Oxford University Press US isbn=0-19-509539-1\n  | }} Timocharis worked with Aristillus in an astronomical observatory\n  | that was most likely part of the Library of Alexandria. Their equipment\n  | would have been simple, most likely consisting of gnomons, sundials and an\n  | armillary sphere. The two were contemporaries of Aristarchus of Samos, but\n  | it is unclear whether there was any association between Timocharis and\n  | Aristarchus. {{cite book first=George | last=Sarton | year=1993\n  | title=Hellenistic science and culture in the last three centuries B.C. |\n  | page=53 publisher=Courier Dover Publications isbn=0-486-27740-2 }}\n\nDuring his astronomical observations, Timocharis recorded that the star Spica\nwas located 8Â° west of the Autumnal equinox. Later, Hipparchus observed that\nSpica was only 6Â° west of the Autumnal equinox. Hipparchus was able to deduce\nthe period during which Timocharis made his observations based upon the records\nof earlier lunar eclipses. From this difference, Hipparchus discovered that the\nlongitudes of the stars had changed over time, which led him to determine the\nfirst value of the precession of the equinoxes as no less than 1/100Â° per\nyear.\n\nIn approximately 3rd century BC, with the help of Aristillus, he created the\nfirst star catalogue in the Western world.\n\nHe made the third recorded mention of Mercury.\n\nThe crater Timocharis on the Moon is named after him. {{cite web\n  | first=Jennifer | last=Blue title=Gazetteer of Planetary Nomenclature\n  | publisher=United States Geological Survey\n  | url=http://planetarynames.wr.usgs.gov/ accessdate=2009-09-10 }}\n","linknr":227,"url":"Timocharis","recorded":1374962822,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Timocharis&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Timocharis&action=edit","//bits.